attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, version 1 (ARM), statically linked, no section header

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is an ARM-based botnet agent, likely a variant of the Gafgyt (Bashlite) or Mirai families, designed for DDoS attacks and remote command execution. Key malicious behaviors include: 1. Persistence and evasion: it forks into the background, calls setsid(), and uses prctl() to mask its process name. 2. Competing malware removal: sub_ef5c scans the /proc filesystem to identify and kill competing bot processes, commonly referred to as a 'killer' module. 3. DDoS capabilities: numerous functions (sub_9704, sub_9e78, sub_bef0, sub_c63c, etc.) implement various flooding techniques, including UDP, TCP, and SYN floods. 4. C2 Communication: it establishes a connection to a hardcoded command-and-control (C2) server at 20.211.168.70. 5. Obfuscation: the binary utilizes a custom string decryption routine (sub_13fa8) to hide sensitive strings and commands, as seen in the initialization function sub_14060.
